TY  - JOUR
T1  - We're Changing—Or Are We? Untangling the Role of Progressive, Regressive, and Stability Narratives During Strategic Change Implementation
AU  - Sonenshein, Scott
Y1  - 2010/06/01
PY  - 2010
DA  - 2010/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.51467638
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.51467638
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 477
EP  - 512
VL  - 53
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Data from a Fortune 500 retailer suggest that managers tell strategically ambiguous, interwoven narratives about how an organization changes and how it remains the same, thereby attempting to both unfreeze and freeze the existing meanings employees attribute to the organization. Employees embellish these narratives to make sense of and narrate responses to change (resisting, championing, and accepting), something patterned by time period and context. This study revises conceptualizations of managerial and employee discourse in fostering and hampering the implementation of strategic change by broadening consideration of both the sources and the types of meanings used to ?construct? change.
AB  - Data from a Fortune 500 retailer suggest that managers tell strategically ambiguous, interwoven narratives about how an organization changes and how it remains the same, thereby attempting to both unfreeze and freeze the existing meanings employees attribute to the organization. Employees embellish these narratives to make sense of and narrate responses to change (resisting, championing, and accepting), something patterned by time period and context. This study revises conceptualizations of managerial and employee discourse in fostering and hampering the implementation of strategic change by broadening consideration of both the sources and the types of meanings used to ?construct? change.
